{"type":"text","timestamp":1778635268716,"sessionID":"ses_1e113f2acffejtzewY8X634XXb","part":{"id":"prt_e1eec6125001iygBChj5KsLAa5","messageID":"msg_e1eec3376001NeM6zx7agfMyfz","sessionID":"ses_1e113f2acffejtzewY8X634XXb","type":"text","text":"History has only the baseline retest and no `LESSONS.md`, so there are no prior structural negatives to avoid. I’m writing a single structural hypothesis focused on decoupling fetch with a small prefetch/skid buffer to recover cycles lost to random instruction backpressure and downstream stalls.","time":{"start":1778635268389,"end":1778635268715},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0b4d0b9ef16840a4016a03d2044968819a952fc36c4ea93f78","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778635277598,"sessionID":"ses_1e113f2acffejtzewY8X634XXb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_qCPvtoWgEQ0o6AvWWvLnzIy9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\n+  inserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\n+  instruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\n+  dmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\n+  is a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\n+  the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure IF into a decoupled fetch producer plus a one- or two-entry\n+  valid/pc/instruction buffer feeding ID. When ID is stalled by load-use or\n+  dmem backpressure and imem is ready, IF should continue advancing and enqueue\n+  sequential instructions; when imemReady drops, ID can consume a buffered\n+  instruction instead of immediately receiving a bubble. Redirects must flush\n+  the buffer and restart at the redirect target. This should improve CoreMark\n+  iterations/cycle under the apples-to-apples random iStall model while adding\n+  only a few registers and muxes, with limited Fmax risk.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the direct combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid/pc/instruction skid buffer, preserving redirect priority and flushing buffered wrong-path entries.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Separate fetch-side stalls from decode-side stalls so imem backpressure only stalls ID when the fetch buffer is empty.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the buffered IF status into the hazard logic and keep the nret=1 RVFI top-level interface unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\n+  inserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\n+  instruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\n+  dmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\n+  is a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\n+  the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure IF into a decoupled fetch producer plus a one- or two-entry\n+  valid/pc/instruction buffer feeding ID. When ID is stalled by load-use or\n+  dmem backpressure and imem is ready, IF should continue advancing and enqueue\n+  sequential instructions; when imemReady drops, ID can consume a buffered\n+  instruction instead of immediately receiving a bubble. Redirects must flush\n+  the buffer and restart at the redirect target. This should improve CoreMark\n+  iterations/cycle under the apples-to-apples random iStall model while adding\n+  only a few registers and muxes, with limited Fmax risk.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the direct combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid/pc/instruction skid buffer, preserving redirect priority and flushing buffered wrong-path entries.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Separate fetch-side stalls from decode-side stalls so imem backpressure only stalls ID when the fetch buffer is empty.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the buffered IF status into the hazard logic and keep the nret=1 RVFI top-level interface unchanged.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\n+  inserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\n+  instruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\n+  dmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\n+  is a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\n+  the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure IF into a decoupled fetch producer plus a one- or two-e