alid/pc/instruction skid buffer, preserving redirect priority and flushing buffered wrong-path entries.\"\n26:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n27:     description: \"Separate fetch-side stalls from decode-side stalls so imem backpressure only stalls ID when the fetch buffer is empty.\"\n28:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n29:     description: \"Wire the buffered IF status into the hazard logic and keep the nret=1 RVFI top-level interface unchanged.\"\n\n(End of file - total 29 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\ntitle: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\n  inserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\n  instruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\n  dmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\n  is a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\n  the single-retire RVFI contract.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure IF into a decoupled fetch producer plus a one- or two-entry\n  valid/pc/instruction buffer feeding ID. When ID is stalled by load-use or\n  dmem backpressure and imem is ready, IF should continue advancing and enqueue\n  sequential instructions; when imemReady drops, ID can consume a buffered\n  instruction instead of immediately receiving a bubble. Redirects must flush\n  the buffer and restart at the redirect target. This should improve CoreMark\n  iterations/cycle under the apples-to-apples random iStall model while adding\n  only a few registers and muxes, with limited Fmax risk.\nexpected_impact:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778635285785,"end":1778635285792}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_081f03b36ac13dcf016a03d2153bec8199bb3519c75770b6ac"}},"id":"prt_e1eeca364001hDYkgBQqBZrVvc","sessionID":"ses_1e113f2acffejtzewY8X634