{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778635313470,"sessionID":"ses_1e113f24affe2BPKmG8kL0dIeR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_apLJZMufqU7anH9aQyiwkKqx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r1s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\n+title: \"Add small BTB branch predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current 5-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch pays a front-end redirect penalty. CoreMark has many tight backward loop branches, and under random instruction-memory stalls each wasted fetch cycle is especially expensive for iterations per cycle.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a small direct-mapped branch target buffer with saturating direction counters, updated in EX and read in IF by the current fetch PC. The IF stage should use a BTB hit with a taken counter to choose the predicted next PC, while ID/EX carries the predicted next PC so EX only redirects on actual-vs-predicted mismatch. This should eliminate most repeated taken-loop penalties after warm-up without changing the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can validate the fetch prediction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement a small BTB/BHT read path and choose the next fetch PC from the predictor on taken hits, with reset-safe invalid entries.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compute the actual next PC, raise redirect only on prediction mismatch, and expose branch predictor update information for taken/not-taken outcomes and targets.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire predictor update signals between EX and IF while preserving the existing NRET=1 RVFI port shape.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r1s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r1s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r1s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r1s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\n+title: \"Add small BTB branch predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current 5-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch pays a front-end redirect penalty. CoreMark has many tight backward loop branches, and under random instruction-memory stalls each wasted fetch cycle is especially expensive for iterations per cycle.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a small direct-mapped branch target buffer with saturating direction counters, updated in EX and read in IF by the current fetch PC. The IF stage should use a BTB hit with a taken counter to choose the predicted next PC, while ID/EX carries the predicted next PC so EX only redirects on actual-vs-predicted mismatch. This should eliminate most repeated taken-loop penalties after warm-up without changing the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can validate the fetch prediction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement a small BTB/BHT read path and choose the 