{"type":"text","timestamp":1778636708166,"sessionID":"ses_1e0fdfa76ffeGqRB5JrCnYuqrw","part":{"id":"prt_e1f0254b40010WMHsFMVlCMVtZ","messageID":"msg_e1f022827002mHVfiykpYAm8LS","sessionID":"ses_1e0fdfa76ffeGqRB5JrCnYuqrw","type":"text","text":"The prior predictor slot already added a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB, so the next focused predictor angle is reducing indirect-return misses rather than enlarging the BTB and lengthening the IF lookup path. I’m writing a RAS hypothesis that complements the BTB with a small, EX-updated call/return predictor.","time":{"start":1778636706996,"end":1778636708165},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_07914189ccee6ee7016a03d7a2dd90819bbffa085c6f31016b","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778636717852,"sessionID":"ses_1e0fdfa76ffeGqRB5JrCnYuqrw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_JyyvwkJFHIPqcSofdKT1gN2m","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\n+title: Add tiny return address stack\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The existing direct-mapped BTB helps repeated fixed-target taken branches, but\n+  it is weak for function returns because a single return instruction can have\n+  different dynamic targets depending on the caller. CoreMark's small C working\n+  set repeatedly calls shared helper routines, so return-target BTB aliasing can\n+  still cause EX-stage redirects even after the BTB is warm.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a very small return address stack in the fetch stage and use lightweight\n+  IF-side instruction predecode to predict JALR returns from x1/x5 using the\n+  stack top. Update the stack only from valid EX-stage resolved control-flow:\n+  push pc+4 for calls that write x1/x5 and pop for JALR returns, avoiding\n+  speculative corruption while preserving precise redirect recovery. This should\n+  complement the current BTB without increasing its associativity or broadening\n+  the main BTB tag/target lookup, improving CoreMark IPC on call-heavy loops at\n+  modest LUT cost.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add compact call/return predictor metadata if needed so EX can classify valid calls and returns without re-decoding in IF-only logic.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a 4-entry return address stack, IF-side return predecode, and prediction priority of redirect over RAS return over existing BTB over pc+4.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Classify resolved JAL/JALR calls and returns, expose RAS push/pop update signals, and keep redirects based on actual next PC versus predicted PC.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire RAS update signals from EX to IF while preserving the nret=1 RVFI and memory port contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\n+title: Add tiny return address stack\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The existing direct-mapped BTB helps repeated fixed-target taken branches, but\n+  it is weak for function returns because a single return instruction can have\n+  different dynamic targets depending on the caller. CoreMark's small C working\n+  set repeatedly calls shared helper routines, so return-target BTB aliasing can\n+  still cause EX-stage redirects even after the BTB is warm.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a very small return address stack in the fetch stage and use lightweight\n+  IF-side instruction predecode to predict JALR returns from x1/x5 using the\n+  stack top. Update the stack only from valid EX-stage resolved control-flow:\n+  push pc+4 for calls that write x1/x5 and pop for JALR returns, avoiding\n+  speculative corruption while preserving precise redirect recovery. This should\n+  complement the current BTB without increasing its associativity or broadening\n+  the main BTB tag/target lookup, improving CoreMark IPC on call-heavy loops at\n+  modest LUT cost.\n+exp