{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778664549465,"sessionID":"ses_1df5663b7ffecagKBrSvLsd6ps","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_egSPM742vODRAYo5JLNH7E1m","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\n+title: \"Drop masked BTB resets\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The successful bench-core micro-optimizations have mostly reduced local state,\n+  fanout, and mux pressure without changing IPC behavior. The current IF-stage\n+  BTB reset loop clears every tag, target, and saturating-counter bit, but those\n+  fields are architecturally irrelevant while the corresponding valid bit is\n+  zero. Keeping reset muxes and reset routing on the whole predictor array may\n+  cost Tang Nano 20K Fmax in the already sensitive fetch next-PC region.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Reset only the BTB valid bits and leave btb_tag, btb_target_word, and btb_ctr\n+  as don't-care state until an entry is allocated. Fetch lookup already requires\n+  btb_valid before comparing tags or using the target/counter, and the update\n+  path initializes tag, target, and counter on every invalid or tag-mismatched\n+  allocation. This should preserve the existing 16-entry direct-mapped BTB\n+  prediction policy and CoreMark cycle count while trimming reset fanout and\n+  sequential muxing from the IF-stage predictor arrays.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Reset only btb_valid entries and rely on allocation writes to initialize tag, target, and counter state before any valid lookup can use them.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypo