{"type":"text","timestamp":1778670868285,"sessionID":"ses_1def73698ffeM2YkNch3jE8WZx","part":{"id":"prt_e210b905e001TGx2c9uDeqV7Bv","messageID":"msg_e210ae1800017avVMCrUcPMs6F","sessionID":"ses_1def73698ffeM2YkNch3jE8WZx","type":"text","text":"I’ll write the hypothesis file now. The proposal targets the next likely hot path after the LSU-address bypass: ADD/ADDI/AUIPC arithmetic still crosses the monolithic RV32IM ALU result mux.","time":{"start":1778670866526,"end":1778670868284},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_019b73e87db97ccb016a045d126d4c819b8ef158707326c7ca","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778670886211,"sessionID":"ses_1def73698ffeM2YkNch3jE8WZx","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_lxiOJAQ7j6EfiyNnbd8JMxJW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r13s0\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for ADD results\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The latest best result came from keeping CoreMark's load/store effective\n+  addresses and jump link values off the monolithic RV32IM ALU result path.\n+  After that change, ordinary ADD/ADDI arithmetic and AUIPC address formation\n+  still route through the full ALU case tree, including the wide M-extension\n+  result muxing, even though these hot operations only need a 32-bit adder.\n+  CoreMark contains frequent pointer increments, loop counters, and pc-relative\n+  address materialization, so shortening the ADD-family writeback/forward path\n+  is a promising local micro-optimization without changing IPC behavior.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated EX-stage add_result path for ALU_ADD arithmetic, using the\n+  same already-selected operands as the current full ALU path, and select it\n+  directly into ex_result for ADD, ADDI, and AUIPC. Keep LOAD/STORE on the\n+  existing LSU address adder, keep JAL/JALR on the direct pc+4 path, and leave\n+  all non-ADD ALU operations, RV32M arithmetic, branch compares, traps,\n+  forwarding, and RVFI fields unchanged. The full ALU can then be operand-gated\n+  away from the most common ADD-family instructions, reducing result mux depth\n+  and routing pressure on the hot execute-to-forward/writeback cone while\n+  preserving the NRET=1 top-level contract and CoreMark cycle count.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated ALU_ADD result adder in EX and select it directly for ADD, ADDI, and AUIPC while keeping LSU, jump, non-ADD ALU, forwarding, and RVFI behavior unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r13s0\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for ADD results\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The latest best result came from keeping CoreMark's load/store effective\n+  addresses and jump link values off the monolithic RV32IM ALU result path.\n+  After that change, ordinary ADD/ADDI arithmetic and AUIPC address formation\n+  still route through the full ALU case tree, including the wide M-extension\n+  result muxing, even though these hot operations only need a 32-bit adder.\n+  CoreMark contains frequent pointer increments, loop counters, and pc-relative\n+  address materialization, so shortening the ADD-family writeback/forward path\n+  is a promising local micro-optimization without changing IPC behavior.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated EX-stage add_result path for ALU_ADD arithmetic, using the\n+  same already-selected operands as the current full ALU path, and select it\n+  directly into ex_result for ADD, ADDI, and AUIPC. Keep LOAD/STORE on the\n+  existing LSU address adder, keep JAL/JALR on the direct pc+4 path, and leave\n+  all non-ADD ALU operations, RV32M arithmetic, branch compares, traps,\n+  forwarding, and RVFI fields unchanged. The full ALU can then be operand-gated\n+  away from the most common ADD-family instructions, reducing result mux depth\n+  and routing pressure on the hot execute-to-forward/writeback cone while\n+  preserving the NRET=1 top-level contract and CoreMark cycle count.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated ALU_ADD result adder in EX and select it directly for ADD, ADDI, and AUIPC while keeping LSU, jump, non-ADD ALU, forwarding, and RVFI behavior unchanged.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r13s0\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for ADD results\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The latest best result came from keeping CoreMark's load/store effective\n+  addresses and jump link values off the monolithic RV32IM ALU result path.\n+  After that change, ordinary ADD/ADDI arithmetic and AUIPC address formation\n+  still route through the full ALU case tree, including the wide M-extension\n+  result muxing, even though these hot operations only need a 32-bit adder.\n+  CoreMark contains frequent pointer increments, loop counters, and pc-relative\n+  address materialization, so shortening the ADD-family writeback/forward path\n+  is a promising local micro-optimization without changing IPC behavior.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated EX-stage add_result path for ALU_ADD arithmetic, using the\n+  same already-selected operands as the current full ALU path, and select it\n+  directly into ex_result for ADD, ADDI, and AUIPC. Keep LOAD/STORE on the\n+  existing LSU address adder, keep JAL/JALR on the direct pc+4 path, and leave\n+  all non-ADD ALU operations, RV32M arithmetic, branch compares, traps,\n+  forwarding, and RVFI fields unchanged. The full ALU can then be operand-gated\n+  away from the most common ADD-family instructions, reducing result mux depth\n+  and routing pressure on the hot execute-to-forward/writeback cone while\n+  preserving the NRET=1 top-level contract and CoreMark cycle count.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated ALU_ADD result adder in EX and select it directly for ADD, ADDI, and AUIPC while keeping LSU, jump, non-ADD ALU, forwarding, and RVFI behavior unchanged.\"\n","additions":28,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r13s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778670886206,"end":1778670886211}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_019b73e87db97ccb016a045d1431b0819bb7683126fe9c809a"}},"id":"prt_e210b973d001ctzAc0n9xF2bbz","sessionID":"ses_1def73698ffeM2YkNch3jE8WZx","messageID":"msg_e210ae1800017avVMCrUcPMs6F"}}
