y count and index width from 16/4 to 32/5, leaving the existing PC-only lookup and EX update semantics intact.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change the BTB entry count ...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Trim BTB tag compare\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current 16-entry direct-mapped BTB remains one of the few successful IPC improvements, but its IF-stage lookup still stores and compares the full 32-bit fetch PC even though the low two alignment bits and the index bits are redundant. Prior predictor-policy and capacity changes regressed by adding front-end logic, so the safer micro-opt path is to keep identical prediction behavior while reducing the lookup cone and state width.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 16-entry direct-mapped BTB remains one of the few successful IPC improvements, but its IF-stage lookup still stores and compares the full 32-bit fetch PC even though the low two alignment bits and the index bits are redundant. Prior predictor-policy and capacity changes regressed by adding front-end logic, so the safer micro-opt path is to keep identical prediction behavior while reducing the lookup cone and state width.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the BTB's full btb_pc array with a compact tag containing only pc[31:BTB_INDEX_BITS+2], and store targets as word addresses plus two implicit zero low bits. The fetch hit check and update same-entry check then use a narrower tag compare, while the existing direct-mapped index, 2-bit counter policy, redirect priority, and EX-stage update semantics stay unchanged. This should slightly shorten the IF next-PC path and reduce LUT/FF pressure without changing CoreMark cycle count or any architectural state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.s