hanges:\n26:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n27:     description: \"Replace variable shifts for load extraction and store masks with explicit addr[1:0] lane mux/decode logic while preserving RVFI and misalignment behavior.\"\n\n(End of file - total 27 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\ntitle: \"Optimize load byte-lane formatter\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current MEM stage formats byte and halfword loads with a variable\n  32-bit right shift by addr[1:0] * 8, then forwards the formatted value\n  directly into the EX-stage operand mux for load-dependent instructions.\n  That creates a likely critical path from dmem read data through a barrel\n  shifter, sign-extension mux, forwarding mux, and ALU/branch compare.\n  CoreMark has frequent loads and dependent address/data use, so improving\n  this path should raise FPGA Fmax without changing the single-retire IPC\n  model or any architectural behavior.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the variable-shift load extraction and shifted byte-mask logic in\n  rtl/mem_stage.sv with explicit case statements keyed by alu_result[1:0].\n  Select byte_val and hword_val directly from dmem_rdata lanes, generate the\n  byte/half/word masks with small decode logic, and keep the existing\n  misalignment trapping, RVFI aligned address reporting, and formatted\n  MEM-stage forwarding semantics unchanged. This is a local micro-optimization\n  intended to reduce LUT depth on the load-to-use forwarding path while","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778642837453,"end":1778642837456}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3c58e58bcb41b3016a03ef951d88819a86002ffce9695051"}},"id":"prt_e1f5fded9001OzVWttzF90zoRZ","sessionID":"ses_1e0a1118dffebzt2ghRURgFtoL","messageID":"msg_e1f5fc172001SXM7gWeKu1pBFq"}}
