{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778646570381,"sessionID":"ses_1e0680950ffeZxzoQM9CK3XRti","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_7UaLf69RCRvAXQmaAOHs2zfx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Consolidate multiply datapath\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current ALU builds three independent 64-bit products for MUL/MULH,\n+  MULHU, and MULHSU on every EX cycle, then selects one result by opcode.\n+  That is expensive on the Tang Nano 20K fabric and likely contributes LUT\n+  pressure and routing delay even when CoreMark mostly uses only a subset of\n+  RV32M multiply forms. Prior attempts show the active win pattern is a local\n+  critical-path/area reduction, not adding broad stall or front-end control.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the three parallel multiplier expressions in rtl/alu.sv with one\n+  signed 33x33 multiply whose operand sign-extension is selected from the\n+  requested MUL-family opcode. The low 32 bits still implement MUL because\n+  signedness does not affect the low product half, while bits [63:32] provide\n+  MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU after choosing signed/signed, unsigned/unsigned, or\n+  signed/unsigned operands. Keep the existing DIV/REM logic and the\n+  RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions unchanged. This should reduce multiplier\n+  LUT/DSP fanout and ALU result mux pressure without changing pipeline timing,\n+  RVFI behavior, or CoreMark cycle count.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Collapse the three parallel MUL-family products into a single signedness-selected 33x33 product while preserving ALTOPS and DIV/REM behavior.\"\n+  - file: test/test_alu.py\n+    description: \"Add or extend directed MULH/MULHU/MULHSU sign-corner vectors to guard the consolidated multiplier against signedness regressions.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Consolidate multiply datapath\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current ALU builds three independent 64-bit products for MUL/MULH,\n+  MULHU, and MULHSU on every EX cycle, then selects one result by opcode.\n+  That is expensive on the Tang Nano 20K fabric and likely contributes LUT\n+  pressure and routing delay even when CoreMark mostly uses only a subset of\n+  RV32M multiply forms. Prior attempts show the active win pattern is a local\n+  critical-path/area reduction, not adding broad stall or front-end control.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the three parallel multiplier expressions in rtl/alu.sv with one\n+  signed 33x33 multiply whose operand sign-extension is selected from the\n+  requested MUL-family opcode. The low 32 bits still implement MUL because\n+  signedness does not affect the low product half, while bits [63:32] provide\n+  MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU after choosing signed/signed, unsigned/unsigned, or\n+  signed/unsigned operands. Keep the existing DIV/REM logic and the\n+  RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions unchanged. This should reduce multiplier\n+  LUT/DSP fanout and ALU result mux pressure without changing pipeline timing,\n+  RVFI behavior, or CoreMark cycle count.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pc