{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778649163377,"sessionID":"ses_1e040dadfffeNVek26p0H9VJr0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_fybuMUcqkSrWaiYOAKB5sewz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\n2: title: \"Drop regfile reset muxes\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current integer register file is implemented as 32 resettable 32-bit\n6:   registers with two combinational read ports and write-first bypassing. That\n7:   forces a reset mux and high-fanout reset control onto every register bit,\n8:   and can prevent the FPGA tools from mapping the small 2R1W file into the\n9:   cheapest distributed storage. Recent wins came from local datapath and LUT\n10:   pressure reductions, while broader control-flow and store decoupling changes\n11:   regressed.\n12: hypothesis: |\n13:   Remove the synchronous reset clearing loop from rtl/reg_file.sv and instead\n14:   give the register array an FPGA/simulation initial value of zero. Keep x0\n15:   hardwired to zero, preserve the same synchronous write and write-first read\n16:   bypass behavior, and leave all raw rs1/rs2 RVFI fields unchanged. Architectural\n17:   RISC-V software cannot depend on nonzero GPR reset contents, and the initial\n18:   zero value preserves existing tests that start from reset, but the synthesized\n19:   design should lose 1024 reset muxes and a large reset fanout tree. This should\n20:   improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax and LUT pressure without changing CoreMark cycle\n21:   count or any memory/control-flow behavior.\n22: expected_impact:\n23:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n24:   confidence: medium\n25: changes:\n26:   - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n27:     description: \"Replace the synchronous reset loop with initialized register storage while preserving x0 reads, write suppression to x0, and same-cycle write-first bypassing.\"\n\n(End of file - total 27 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\ntitle: \"Drop regfile reset muxes\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current integer register file is implemented as 32 resettable 32-bit\n  registers with two combinational read ports and write-first bypassing. That\n  forces a reset mux and high-fanout reset control onto every register bit,\n  and can prevent the FPGA tools from mapping the small 2R1W file into the\n  cheapest distributed storage. Recent wins came from local datapath and LUT\n  pressure reductions, while broader control-flow and store decoupling changes\n  regressed.\nhypothesis: |\n  Remove the synchronous reset clearing loop from rtl/reg_file.sv and instead\n  give the register array an FPGA/simulation initial value of zero. Keep x0\n  hardwired to zero, preserve the same synchronous write and write-first read\n  bypass behavior, and leave all raw rs1/rs2 RVFI fields unchanged. Architectural\n  RISC-V software cannot depend on nonzero GPR reset contents, and the initial\n  zero value preserves existing tests that start from reset, but the synthesized\n  design should lose 1024 reset muxes and a large reset fanout tree. This should\n  improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax and LUT pressure without changing CoreMark cycle","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778649163370,"end":1778649163376}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_040f66bd896402ed016a04084b3984819ba24dc52aaa465c7d"}},"id":"prt_e1fc06659001SbxTqjqvDHKRlo","sessionID":"ses_1e040dadfffeNVek26p0H9VJr0","messageID":"msg_e1fc03a5f00184yDIl0BeTrciJ"}}
