{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778662252390,"sessionID":"ses_1df7a4916ffe8B8q0dMz2Ncyu1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_ujDLlptGuclO9iip7lFX2Yqm","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n+title: \"Split commit and RVFI state\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that changed frontend timing, removed MEM/WB,\n+  or added same-cycle load forwarding regressed or broke because they either\n+  lengthened hot control paths or removed state needed during dmem stalls.\n+  The strongest wins instead came from pruning payload and reducing fanout.\n+  MEM/WB is still required as a stable retirement and forwarding boundary,\n+  but the current single wide mem_wb_t mixes hot writeback/forwarding fields\n+  with RVFI-only bookkeeping that does not need to feed the regfile or hazard\n+  paths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure the MEM/WB boundary into two parallel records: a narrow hot\n+  writeback/forward record containing valid, rd, reg_write, mem_to_reg,\n+  alu_result, and read_data, plus a separate RVFI shadow record containing\n+  pc, instruction, source snapshots, memory masks/data, and trap metadata.\n+  The hot record should be the only state seen by wb_stage, forward_unit,\n+  and regfile writeback, while core.sv drives RVFI from the shadow record at\n+  the same retirement boundary and with the same rvfi_order behavior. This\n+  keeps the proven MEM/WB hold semantics for dmem stalls while reducing fanout\n+  and routing pressure from wide RVFI fields on timing-critical writeback and\n+  forwarding cones.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add separate packed types for the narrow MEM/WB writeback record and the RVFI-only retirement shadow record, preserving the existing NRET=1 external RVFI fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Drive both records at the MEM/WB boundary and preserve hold-on-dmem-stall semantics so forwarding state remains stable while valid is suppressed.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume only the narrow writeback record instead of the full RVFI-bearing MEM/WB payload.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the split MEM/WB records through writeback, forwarding, and RVFI generation without changing top-level ports or retirement ordering.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n+title: \"Split commit and RVFI state\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that changed frontend timing, removed MEM/WB,\n+  or added same-cycle load forwarding regressed or broke because they either\n+  lengthened hot control paths or removed state needed during dmem stalls.\n+  The strongest wins instead came from pruning payload and reducing fanout.\n+  MEM/WB is still required as a stable retirement and forwarding boundary,\n+  but the current single wide mem_wb_t mixes hot writeback/forwarding fields\n+  with RVFI-only bookkeeping that does not need to feed the regfile or hazard\n+  paths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure the MEM/WB boundary into two parallel records: a narrow hot\n+  writeback/fo