{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778664594249,"sessionID":"ses_1df56634cffeA8ilqgDJLgvhwn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Cu5DHXi8KMxrNkyDkuXy84i9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r11s1\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for LSU addresses\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark spends much of its timed region in pointer-heavy load/store code, and the\n+  current EX stage routes every memory effective address through the same monolithic\n+  RV32IM ALU result bus used for arithmetic, multiply, divide, and writeback values.\n+  Recent structural attempts that added buffers or changed retirement boundaries\n+  regressed, while local datapath isolation and payload pruning have produced the\n+  strongest gains.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure EX so instruction classes have separate result producers: a dedicated\n+  rs1+imm address adder for LOAD/STORE, the existing branch/jump target adders for\n+  control flow, a direct pc+4 path for JAL/JALR writeback, and the full ALU output\n+  only for arithmetic instructions that actually need it. EX/MEM should receive the\n+  LSU address from the small address adder instead of the full ALU mux whenever\n+  mem_read or mem_write is set, while all hazards, forwarding, dmem stall behavior,\n+  misalignment checks, and RVFI fields remain unchanged. This should shorten the\n+  common load/store address-to-MEM path and reduce full-ALU fanout without adding\n+  bubbles or predictor state.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated LSU effective-address adder and select it for EX/MEM alu_result on memory operations, keeping the full ALU result only for arithmetic writeback paths.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r11s1\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for LSU addresses\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark spends much of its timed region in pointer-heavy load/store code, and the\n+  current EX stage routes every memory effective address through the same monolithic\n+  RV32IM ALU result bus used for arithmetic, multiply, divide, and writeback values.\n+  Recent structural attempts that added buffers or changed retirement boundaries\n+  regressed, while local datapath isolation and payload pruning have produced the\n+  strongest gains.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure EX so instruction classes have separate result producers: a dedicated\n+  rs1+imm address adder for LOAD/STORE, the existing branch/jump target adders for\n+  control flow, a direct pc+4 path for JAL/JALR writeback, and the full ALU output\n+  only for arithmetic instructions that actually need it. EX/MEM should receive the\n+  LSU address from the small address adder instead of the full ALU mux whenever\n+  mem_read or mem_write is set, while all hazards, forwarding, dmem stall behavior,\n+  misalignment checks, and RVFI fields remain unchanged. This should shorten the\n+  common load/store address-to-MEM path and reduce full-ALU fanout without adding\n+  bubbles or predictor state.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"A