{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778670812280,"sessionID":"ses_1def73626ffeYKtoPSemtBHeh1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_1sxFRTzKNRrG9G2LXktjZ9Rz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n2: title: \"Add fast addsub execute lane\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The latest successful structural change improved fitness by splitting common\n6:   CoreMark LOAD/STORE and JAL/JALR result producers away from the monolithic\n7:   RV32IM ALU. The remaining hot integer address-update and loop-counter work\n8:   still routes ADD, ADDI, SUB, and AUIPC through the full ALU case tree and\n9:   output mux that also contains shifts, compares, multiply, divide, and\n10:   remainder. Prior broad execute-lane splits regressed when they added M-op\n11:   control and duplicate routing, so the safer structural angle is a very narrow\n12:   fast lane for the most common add/sub class only.\n13: hypothesis: |\n14:   Restructure EX so ADD/ADDI/SUB/AUIPC arithmetic has a dedicated fast adder\n15:   lane beside the existing LSU address adder and JAL pc+4 path. For these\n16:   opcodes, drive the EX/MEM result from the small add/sub lane and gate the\n17:   full ALU inputs to zero; keep the existing ALU for logic, shifts, compares,\n18:   LUI, and all RV32M operations. This should shorten CoreMark's frequent\n19:   integer update writeback path and reduce full-ALU result mux pressure without\n20:   changing pipeline depth, load-use interlocks, forwarding, traps, RVFI fields,\n21:   or the NRET=1 top-level contract.\n22: expected_impact:\n23:   fitness_delta_pct: 4\n24:   confidence: medium\n25: changes:\n26:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n27:     description: \"Add a dedicated ADD/ADDI/SUB/AUIPC fast result lane, select it before the full ALU for those arithmetic ops, and gate full-ALU operands when the fast lane is used.\"\n28:   - file: rtl/alu.sv\n29:     description: \"Optionally remove or leave unreachable ADD/SUB pressure after EX gating, while preserving logic, shift, compare, LUI, RV32M, and ALTOPS behavior exactly.\"\n\n(End of file - total 29 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\ntitle: \"Add fast addsub execute lane\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The latest successful structural change improved fitness by splitting common\n  CoreMark LOAD/STORE and JAL/JALR result producers away from the monolithic\n  RV32IM ALU. The remaining hot integer address-update and loop-counter work\n  still routes ADD, ADDI, SUB, and AUIPC through the full ALU case tree and\n  output mux that also contains shifts, compares, multiply, divide, and\n  remainder. Prior broad execute-lane splits regressed when they added M-op\n  control and duplicate routing, so the safer structural angle is a very narrow\n  fast lane for the most common add/sub class only.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure EX so ADD/ADDI/SUB/AUIPC arithmetic has a dedicated fast adder\n  lane beside the existing LSU address adder and JAL pc+4 path. For these\n  opcodes, drive the EX/MEM result from the small add/sub lane and gate the\n  full ALU inputs to zero; keep the existing ALU for logic, shifts, compares,\n  LUI, and all RV32M operations. This should shorten CoreMark's frequent\n  integer update writeback path and reduce full-ALU result mux pressure without\n  changing pipeline depth, load-use interlocks, forwarding, traps, RVFI fields,","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778670812273,"end":1778670812279}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_