{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778675461149,"sessionID":"ses_1deb04b84ffetArzI5J9WVDGov","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_cNHzzWBweCE6kbFVAXKD4QvJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r15s1\n+title: \"Split EX result and LSU address buses\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX/MEM payload still uses one alu_result bus for two different\n+  roles: arithmetic/jump writeback data and the LOAD/STORE effective address.\n+  The successful LSU-address bypass already showed that keeping pointer-heavy\n+  memory traffic away from the full RV32IM ALU helps, but MEM still fans this\n+  shared result into dmem address, byte-mask decode, misalignment checks,\n+  load-lane selection, forwarding, and writeback muxing. Prior structural\n+  attempts that added buffers, broader execute lanes, or new stall policy\n+  regressed, so the safer next step is to reduce datapath fanout without\n+  changing pipeline depth or behavior.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split ex_mem_t's single alu_result into separate wb_result and mem_addr\n+  fields. EX should drive wb_result with the arithmetic/JAL/AUIPC result used\n+  for forwarding and register writeback, while mem_addr is driven only by the\n+  dedicated rs1+imm LSU adder for LOAD/STORE operations. MEM should use mem_addr\n+  for dmem ports, byte masks, misalignment checks, RVFI memory address, and\n+  load lane selection, while wb_result feeds non-load forwarding and writeback.\n+  This keeps the proven five-stage, single-retire pipeline and all existing\n+  load-use, dmem-stall, trap, and RVFI semantics unchanged, but removes hot\n+  arithmetic writeback values from memory-formatting fanout and removes LSU\n+  addresses from the arithmetic writeback cone.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Replace ex_mem_t.alu_result with separate wb_result and mem_addr fields so post-EX datapaths no longer share one wide bus.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Drive wb_result from arithmetic or pc+4 producers and mem_addr from the dedicated LSU address adder, preserving existing redirect and trap behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use mem_addr for all dmem, mask, misalignment, and RVFI memory fields while using wb_result for non-load forwarding and MEM/WB writeback.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r15s1\n+title: \"Split EX result and LSU address buses\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX/MEM payload still uses one alu_result bus for two different\n+  roles: arithmetic/jump writeback data and the LOAD/STORE effective address.\n+  The successful LSU-address bypass already showed that keeping pointer-heavy\n+  memory traffic away from the full RV32IM ALU helps, but MEM still fans this\n+  shared result into dmem address, byte-mask decode, misalignment checks,\n+  load-lane selection, forwarding, and writeback muxing. Prior structural\n+  attempts that added buffers, broader execute lanes, or new stall policy\n+  regressed, so the safer next step is to reduce datapath fanout without\n+  changing pipeline depth or behavior.\n+hypot