data, if needed, to identify DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as multi-cycle EX operations without changing the NRET=1 RVFI bundle shape.\"\n26:   - file: rtl/alu.sv\n27:     description: \"Remove real DIV/REM from the one-cycle combinational ALU path while keeping normal ALU, MUL-family, and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS results consistent.\"\n28:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n29:     description: \"Instantiate or integrate a small multi-cycle divider/remainder unit, hold the EX instruction until completion, and drive the final result into EX/MEM exactly once.\"\n30:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n31:     description: \"Add an EX multi-cycle stall input that freezes IF/ID and ID/EX without creating duplicate retirements, with redirect and dmem-stall priority preserved.\"\n32:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n33:     description: \"Wire the divider-busy stall between EX and the hazard logic while preserving the existing top-level IO and single-channel RVFI contract.\"\n34:   - file: test/test_alu.py\n35:     description: \"Extend or preserve RV32M division and remainder vectors so the sidecar's divide-by-zero and signed-overflow corner cases remain covered.\"\n\n(End of file - total 35 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\ntitle: \"Move div/rem off EX critical path\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current ALU keeps RV32M division and remainder as single-cycle\n  combinational operations in the EX stage. CoreMark's timed path is dominated\n  by loads, branches, integer ALU work, and multiplication, while DIV/REM are\n  rare or absent. Keeping a full divider on every EX-cycle timing path likely\n  costs Fmax and LUTs without improving CoreMark iterations per cycle.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split the M-extension structure so common ALU operations and MUL/MULH stay on\n  the existing one-cycle EX path, but DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU are handled by a small\n  multi-cycle divider sidecar that stalls the pipeline only when one of those\n  opcodes reaches EX. This should remove the long combinational divide/remainder\n  network from the EX/MEM register timing path and recover FPGA Fmax, while\n  preserving CoreMark IPC because the benchmark should not depend on frequent\n  divisions. The sidecar must keep RV32M corner-case results exact, keep ALTOPS\n  behavior for fast formal runs, and retire the original instruction only after\n  the computed result is available.\nexpected_impact:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778642867920,"end":1778642867923}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0ebef23a95d87e21016a03efb38018819b98fccc2502d4c3c5"}},"id":"prt_e1f60558c001kkFSuCIbvDWvSb","sessionID":"ses_1e0a1111bffeeHsqnmeRCd93cW","messageID":"msg_e1f604126001YZ8bwr3UrRFPjS"}}
