{"type":"text","timestamp":1778646529732,"sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","part":{"id":"prt_e1f9828dd001LfyVgAsR90CJfz","messageID":"msg_e1f981a88001qqrkeV6yZolpo4","sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","type":"text","text":"The log confirms prior structural attempts: fetch skid buffering regressed by adding IF mux/control depth, early ID control-flow resolution regressed badly, and a DIV/REM sidecar regressed by adding global stall/result muxing. I’m focusing the new structural hypothesis on shortening the hot forwarding/register-file structure without adding front-end control complexity.","time":{"start":1778646526173,"end":1778646529731},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_07b151ef2962a063016a03fdfe1558819a956ed6362f794461","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778646529759,"sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_EAlRtlFpS2hCStr11FzqvfhS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":3,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\\ninserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\\ninstruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\\ndmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\\nis a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\\nthe single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\\ninserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\\ninstruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\\ndmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\\nis a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\\nthe single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure IF into a decoupled fetch producer plus a one- or two-entry\\nvalid/pc/instruction buffer feeding ID. When ID is stalled by load-use or\\ndmem backpressure and imem is ready, IF should continue advancing and enqueue\\nsequential instructions; when imemReady drops, ID can consume a buffered\\ninstruction instead of immediately receiving a bubble. Redirects must flush\\nthe buffer and restart at the redirect target. This should improve CoreMark\\niterations/cycle under the apples-to-apples random iStall model while adding\\nonly a few registers and muxes, with limited Fmax risk.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the direct combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid/pc/instruction skid buffer, preserving redirect priority and flushing buffered wrong-path entries.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Separate fetch-side stalls from decode-side stalls so imem backpressure only st... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 3-3 of 10. Use offset=4 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\\ninserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\\ninstruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\\ndmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\\nis a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\\nthe single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\\ninserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\\ninstruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\\ndmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\\nis a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\\nthe single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure IF into a decoupled fetch producer plus a one- or two-entry\\nvalid/pc/instruction buffer feeding ID. When ID is stalled by load-use or\\ndmem backpressure and imem is ready, IF should continue advancing and enqueue\\nsequential instructions; when imemReady drops, ID can consume a buffered\\ninstruction instead of immediately receiving a bubble. Redirects must flush\\nthe buffer and restart at the redirect target. This should improve CoreMark\\niterations/cycle under the apples-to-apples random iStall model while adding\\nonly a few registers and muxes, with limited Fmax risk.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the direct combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid/pc/instruction skid buffer, preserving redirect priority and flushing buffered wrong-path entries.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Separate fetch-side stalls from decode-side stalls so imem backpressure only st... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778646529756,"end":1778646529759}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07b151ef2962a063016a03fe01a1dc819ab9b7b9d46576fc68"}},"id":"prt_e1f9836c8001C6QPt4OJqz4OSm","sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","messageID":"msg_e1f981a88001qqrkeV6yZolpo4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778646529893,"sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5imKRdSSRFslzfrHB7a3Gc7S","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":6,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve simple control flow in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline resolves every branch and jump in EX, so taken control\\nflow still carries a two-stage wrong-path penalty unless the BTB predicts it\\ncorrectly. The prior structural fetch skid buffer lost because it added IF\\ncontrol and muxing without shortening a common dependency path. CoreMark has\\nmany loop branches and unconditional jumps, so structurally moving simple\\ntarget/condition resolution one stage earlier can improve iterations/cycle\\nwithout widening retirement or adding front-end buffering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline resolves every branch and jump in EX, so taken control\\nflow still carries a two-stage wrong-path penalty unless the BTB predicts it\\ncorrectly. The prior structural fetch skid buffer lost because it added IF\\ncontrol and muxing without shortening a common dependency path. CoreMark has\\nmany loop branches and unconditional jumps, so structurally moving simple\\ntarget/condition resolution one stage earlier can improve iterations/cycle\\nwithout widening retirement or adding front-end buffering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an early-control path in ID for JAL and branch instructions whose operands\\nare already available from the regfile or WB write-first bypass, and redirect\\nIF before the instruction reaches EX. ID/EX should carry an early-resolved\\nnext PC plus a flag so EX can skip reissuing the same redirect while still\\npreserving the existing EX resolution for forwarded operands, load-use cases,\\nJALR, misalignment traps, and predictor updates. This reduces taken JAL and\\nmany non-dependent loop branch penalties by one cycle while keeping the\\nsingle-retire RVFI boundary and trap discipline unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ID/EX metadata for an early-resolved next PC and whether E... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 6-6 of 10. Use offset=7 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve simple control flow in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline resolves every branch and jump in EX, so taken control\\nflow still carries a two-stage wrong-path penalty unless the BTB predicts it\\ncorrectly. The prior structural fetch skid buffer lost because it added IF\\ncontrol and muxing without shortening a common dependency path. CoreMark has\\nmany loop branches and unconditional jumps, so structurally moving simple\\ntarget/condition resolution one stage earlier can improve iterations/cycle\\nwithout widening retirement or adding front-end buffering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline resolves every branch and jump in EX, so taken control\\nflow still carries a two-stage wrong-path penalty unless the BTB predicts it\\ncorrectly. The prior structural fetch skid buffer lost because it added IF\\ncontrol and muxing without shortening a common dependency path. CoreMark has\\nmany loop branches and unconditional jumps, so structurally moving simple\\ntarget/condition resolution one stage earlier can improve iterations/cycle\\nwithout widening retirement or adding front-end buffering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an early-control path in ID for JAL and branch instructions whose operands\\nare already available from the regfile or WB write-first bypass, and redirect\\nIF before the instruction reaches EX. ID/EX should carry an early-resolved\\nnext PC plus a flag so EX can skip reissuing the same redirect while still\\npreserving the existing EX resolution for forwarded operands, load-use cases,\\nJALR, misalignment traps, and predictor updates. This reduces taken JAL and\\nmany non-dependent loop branch penalties by one cycle while keeping the\\nsingle-retire RVFI boundary and trap discipline unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ID/EX metadata for an early-resolved next PC and whether E... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778646529889,"end":1778646529893}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07b151ef2962a063016a03fe01a1f0819a95fb9b752db183b7"}},"id":"prt_e1f9836dd001GJuOfelOA7MCqE","sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","messageID":"msg_e1f981a88001qqrkeV6yZolpo4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778646529894,"sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_KCI2QfmXaFhEjD9ntFKZmA7G","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":9,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Move div/rem off EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU keeps RV32M division and remainder as single-cycle\\ncombinational operations in the EX stage. CoreMark's timed path is dominated\\nby loads, branches, integer ALU work, and multiplication, while DIV/REM are\\nrare or absent. Keeping a full divider on every EX-cycle timing path likely\\ncosts Fmax and LUTs without improving CoreMark iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU keeps RV32M division and remainder as single-cycle\\ncombinational operations in the EX stage. CoreMark's timed path is dominated\\nby loads, branches, integer ALU work, and multiplication, while DIV/REM are\\nrare or absent. Keeping a full divider on every EX-cycle timing path likely\\ncosts Fmax and LUTs without improving CoreMark iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the M-extension structure so common ALU operations and MUL/MULH stay on\\nthe existing one-cycle EX path, but DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU are handled by a small\\nmulti-cycle divider sidecar that stalls the pipeline only when one of those\\nopcodes reaches EX. This should remove the long combinational divide/remainder\\nnetwork from the EX/MEM register timing path and recover FPGA Fmax, while\\npreserving CoreMark IPC because the benchmark should not depend on frequent\\ndivisions. The sidecar must keep RV32M corner-case results exact, keep ALTOPS\\nbehavior for fast formal runs, and retire the original instruction only after\\nthe computed result is available.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact control metadata, if needed, to identify DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as multi-cycle EX operations without changing the NRET=1 RVFI bundle shape.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM from the one-cycle combinational ALU path while keeping normal ALU, MUL-family, and RISCV_FORM... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 9-9 of 10. Use offset=10 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Move div/rem off EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU keeps RV32M division and remainder as single-cycle\\ncombinational operations in the EX stage. CoreMark's timed path is dominated\\nby loads, branches, integer ALU work, and multiplication, while DIV/REM are\\nrare or absent. Keeping a full divider on every EX-cycle timing path likely\\ncosts Fmax and LUTs without improving CoreMark iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU keeps RV32M division and remainder as single-cycle\\ncombinational operations in the EX stage. CoreMark's timed path is dominated\\nby loads, branches, integer ALU work, and multiplication, while DIV/REM are\\nrare or absent. Keeping a full divider on every EX-cycle timing path likely\\ncosts Fmax and LUTs without improving CoreMark iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the M-extension structure so common ALU operations and MUL/MULH stay on\\nthe existing one-cycle EX path, but DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU are handled by a small\\nmulti-cycle divider sidecar that stalls the pipeline only when one of those\\nopcodes reaches EX. This should remove the long combinational divide/remainder\\nnetwork from the EX/MEM register timing path and recover FPGA Fmax, while\\npreserving CoreMark IPC because the benchmark should not depend on frequent\\ndivisions. The sidecar must keep RV32M corner-case results exact, keep ALTOPS\\nbehavior for fast formal runs, and retire the original instruction only after\\nthe computed result is available.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact control metadata, if needed, to identify DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as multi-cycle EX operations without changing the NRET=1 RVFI bundle shape.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM from the one-cycle combinational ALU path while keeping normal ALU, MUL-family, and RISCV_FORM... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778646529890,"end":1778646529894}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07b151ef2962a063016a03fe01a1f8819aa25efc3c5a3dc4be"}},"id":"prt_e1f98376100209TIBLXKPUCZrf","sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","messageID":"msg_e1f981a88001qqrkeV6yZolpo4"}}
