{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778646648088,"sessionID":"ses_1e06809b2ffeHGTgP6G1vzU1HB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_1Ob8QTBTw5HCcHymW22U7DKy","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\n+title: \"Post ordinary RAM stores\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes the entire core whenever a store sits in MEM\n+  and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode dmem has random\n+  backpressure, and CoreMark contains many stores whose results are not\n+  immediately consumed by the next integer instructions. Prior structural\n+  attempts regressed by lengthening the fetch/control critical path; this\n+  targets a different bottleneck by decoupling store acceptance from the\n+  rest of the in-order pipeline.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry posted store buffer for aligned, non-MMIO RAM stores. When a\n+  store reaches MEM while dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated\n+  write data, byte mask, and RVFI store fields, allow the store to retire once\n+  it is safely enqueued, and continue executing independent non-memory\n+  instructions while the buffer drains to dmem in the background. Preserve\n+  architectural ordering by stalling any later load or store until the buffer\n+  is empty, and never post UART or CoreMark timing-marker MMIO stores so the\n+  start/stop bracket remains tied to real bus writes. This should improve\n+  CoreMark iterations/cycle under random dStall without adding predictor or\n+  branch-resolution logic to the critical IF path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry posted store buffer for aligned normal-RAM stores, drive buffered writes to dmem when ready, and retire stores after enqueue while keeping existing RVFI masks/data exact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Change dmem stall policy so loads, MMIO stores, full-buffer stores, and younger memory operations still block, while independent non-memory instructions can pass a pending posted store.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer busy/full and post-eligibility status between MEM and the hazard unit without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,32 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\n+title: \"Post ordinary RAM stores\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes the entire core whenever a store sits in MEM\n+  and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode dmem has random\n+  backpressure, and CoreMark contains many stores whose results are not\n+  immediately consumed by the next integer instructions. Prior structural\n+  attempts regressed by lengthening the fetch/control critical path; this\n+  targets a different bottleneck by decoupling store acceptance from the\n+  rest of the in-order pipeline.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry posted store buffer for aligned, non-MMIO RAM stores. When a\n+  store reaches MEM while dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated\n+  write data, byte mask, and RVFI store fields, allow the store to retire once\n+  it is safely enqueued, and continue executing independent non-memory\n+  instructions while the buffer drains to dmem in the background. Preserve\n+  architectural ordering by stalling any later load or store until the buffer\n+  is empty, and never post UART or CoreMark timing-marker MMIO stores so the\n+  start/stop bracket remains tied to real bus writes. This should improve\n+  CoreMark iterations/cycle under random dStall without adding predictor or\n+  branch-resolution logic to the critical IF path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry posted store buffer for aligned normal-RAM stores, drive buffered writes to dmem when ready, and retire stores after enqueue while keeping existing RVFI masks/data exact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Change dmem stall policy so loads, MMIO stores, full-buffer stores, and younger memory operations still block, while independent non-memory instructions can pass a pending posted store.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer busy/full and post-eligibility status between MEM and the hazard unit without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r4s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/benc