{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778654507526,"sessionID":"ses_1dfef2dc9ffeb4JrjTdHbLGYS2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_2JS2kP4JSjMue1lFhwwUCCqW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Use zero-bubble load forwarding\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline still injects a one-cycle bubble for every true load-use\n+  dependency even though MEM-stage forwarding already formats load data and can\n+  feed the EX operand muxes. CoreMark has many pointer-chasing and state-update\n+  sequences where removing those bubbles should improve iterations per cycle.\n+  Prior structural attempts lost by adding front-end or store-buffer control;\n+  this keeps the pipeline shape intact and changes only the interlock policy.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure the load-use path so a consumer immediately behind a load is\n+  allowed to enter EX while the load is in MEM, using the existing EX/MEM\n+  forwarding select to supply formatted load data directly from mem_stage.\n+  If dmem backpressure occurs, the existing dmem stall should hold both the\n+  load in MEM and the dependent consumer in ID/EX until data is available, so\n+  correctness remains in-order without adding a new buffer. This trades a\n+  longer dmem-to-EX bypass path for fewer CoreMark dependency bubbles; the\n+  previous lane-mux load formatter win makes that timing path cheaper than it\n+  was before.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the unconditional load-use bubble and rely on dmem stalls plus MEM-stage load forwarding for true dependent consumers.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Keep EX operand, branch, JALR, and store-data forwarding compatible with same-cycle MEM load results, preserving RVFI source snapshots.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Audit the formatted load forwarding output so it remains valid only when the MEM load is ready and trap-gated as today.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Use zero-bubble load forwarding\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline still injects a one-cycle bubble for every true load-use\n+  dependency even though MEM-stage forwarding already formats load data and can\n+  feed the EX operand muxes. CoreMark has many pointer-chasing and state-update\n+  sequences where removing those bubbles should improve iterations per cycle.\n+  Prior structural attempts lost by adding front-end or store-buffer control;\n+  this keeps the pipeline shape intact and changes only the interlock policy.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure the load-use path so a consumer immediately behind a load is\n+  allowed to enter EX while the load is in MEM, using the existing EX/MEM\n+  forwarding select to supply formatted load data directly from mem_stage.\n+  If dmem backpressure occurs, the existing dmem stall should hold both the\n+  load in MEM and the dependent consumer in ID/EX until data is available, so\n+  correctness remains in-order without adding a new buffer. This trades a\n+  longer dmem-to-EX bypass path for fewer CoreMark dependency bubbles; the\n+  previous lane-mux load formatter win makes that timing path cheaper than it\n+  was before.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the unconditional load-use bubble and rely on dmem stalls plus MEM-stage load forwarding for true dependent consumers.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Keep EX operand, branch, JALR, and store-data forwarding compatible with same-cycle MEM load results, preserving RVFI source snapshots.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Audit the formatted load forwarding output so it remains valid only when the MEM load is ready and trap-gated as today.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Use zero-bubble load forwarding\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline still injects a one-cycle bubble for every true load-use\n+  dependency even though MEM-stage forwarding already formats load data and can\n+  feed the EX operand muxes. CoreMark has many pointer-chasing and state-update\n+  sequences where removing those bubbles should improve iterations per cycle.\n+  Prior structur