{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778656687635,"sessionID":"ses_1dfce6a2effeX23v3w0HOigY2k","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_1MrZjb4pBLqnpl4OiszxLDyR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r8s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r8s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\n2: title: \"Retire directly from MEM\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current bench core still carries a full MEM/WB register and a separate\n6:   combinational WB stage even though MEM already computes the final writeback\n7:   value, formatted load data, memory masks, and RVFI memory fields. Recent wins\n8:   came from pruning dead pipeline payload and shortening local datapath cones,\n9:   while prior structural regressions came from adding front-end buffers,\n10:   earlier branch logic, store buffers, or same-cycle dmem-to-EX pressure. A\n11:   MEM-stage retirement boundary attacks pipeline structure and routing pressure\n12:   without adding predictor state or changing the NRET=1 contract.\n13: hypothesis: |\n14:   Collapse writeback/retirement into the MEM stage: compute the final rd write\n15:   data from the current EX/MEM payload, write the regfile from that MEM-stage\n16:   commit value, and drive RVFI channel 0 from the same commit record when the\n17:   memory operation is actually accepted. Keep the existing one-cycle load-use\n18:   interlock, but remove the broad MEM/WB payload and replace MEM/WB forwarding\n19:   with MEM-stage forwarding plus the regfile's same-cycle write-first bypass\n20:   for instructions two cycles behind a producer. This should reduce flop count,\n21:   forwarding mux fan-in, and routing fanout on every instruction while keeping\n22:   CoreMark's steady-state single-retire IPC and bus-ordering semantics intact.\n23: expected_impact:\n24:   fitness_delta_pct: 4\n25:   confidence: medium\n26: changes:\n27:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n28:     description: \"Move the retirement/writeback boundary from MEM/WB to MEM-stage commit signals, delete the wb_stage instance, and keep rvfi_order tied to accepted MEM commits.\"\n29:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n30:     description: \"Expose final commit fields, formatted load data, masks, and regfile writeback data directly from the current EX/MEM payload while gating valid during dmem stalls.\"\n31:   - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n32:     description: \"Reduce forwarding to the current MEM-stage producer plus regfile write-first behavior, eliminating the MEM/WB producer input.\"\n33:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n34:     description: \"Remove or shrink the MEM/WB bundle after RVFI commit fields are generated directly at MEM-stage retirement.\"\n35:   - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n36:     description: \"Delete the now-redundant standalone writeback mux or leave it unused if the implementation keeps the file for build ordering simplicity.\"\n\n(End of file - total 36 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\ntitle: \"Retire directly from MEM\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current bench core still carries a full MEM/WB register and a separate\n  combinational WB stage even though MEM already computes the final writeback\n  value, formatted load data, memory masks, and RVFI memory fields. Recent wins\n  came from pruning dead pipeline payload and shortening local datapath cones,\n  while prior structural regressions came from adding front-end buffers,\n  earlier branch logic, store buffers, or same-cycle dmem-to-EX pressure. A\n  MEM-stage retirement boundary attacks pipeline structure and routing pressure\n  without adding predictor state or changing the NRET=1 contract.\nhypothesis: |\n  Collapse writeback/retirement into the MEM stage: compute the final rd write\n  data from the current EX/MEM payload, write the regfile from that MEM-stage\n  commit value, and drive RVFI channel 0 from the same commit record when the\n  memory operation is actually accepted. Keep the existing one-cycle load-use\n  interlock, but remove the broad MEM/WB payload and replace MEM/WB forwarding\n  with MEM-stage forwarding plus the regfile's same-cycle write-first bypass\n  for instructions two cycles behind a producer. This should reduce flop count,","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r8s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778656687620,"end":1778656687634}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_041445aba0398985016a0425af8010819b8e3b0e84e7f0a34a"}},"id":"prt_e203335f6001nwMjpO4ZzfRfaa","sessionID":"ses_1dfce6a2effeX23v3w0HOigY2k","messageID":"msg_e20330922001qRFVh9rEs0c6tG"}}
