{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778659908564,"sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_7YpeveG6UZgjYi6jdDMkrQD3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predecode may gate load-use stalls, but it must not mask RVFI rs1/rs2 fields because cosim expects raw instruction register fields and pre-write snapshots even when operands are unused.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (regression, +0.95%): A two-entry IF skid buffer added enough PC/buffer/valid-control muxing to outweigh its limited CoreMark benefit under random iStall, so fetch-ahead only helps if the core can exploit buffered instructions without extending the front-end critical path.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (improvement, +0.96%): A tiny direct-mapped BTB helps CoreMark's repeated taken loops by avoiding warm branch redirects, but IF-side predictor lookup/update logic and aliasing keep the gain modest.\n4: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (improvement, +1.89%): Opcode-aware load-use gating recovers CoreMark bubbles from immediate/address-update code, but true load consumers still need raw RVFI source fields plus formatted MEM-stage load forwarding.\n5: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -40.43%): Pulling JAL/branch resolution into ID added regfile-compare, dependency-check, target-add, and IF redirect muxing onto the front-end path, so CoreMark control-flow savings did not offset the critical-path cost.\n6: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (broken, n/a): A fetch-stage RAS with IF-side JALR predecode and data-dependent stack indexing can make riscv-formal intractable, so predictor additions need solver-friendly state updates as well as correct architectural recovery.\n7: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (improvement, +4.91%): Replacing variable-shift load formatting with addr[1:0] lane muxes shortens the dmem-to-forwarding critical path for CoreMark's load-dependent code without changing MEM-stage semantics.\n8: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -17.42%): Moving DIV/REM into a sidecar can regress CoreMark when the divider is not the active critical path, because multi_stall gating and commit-result/operand muxes still sit on every EX instruction.\n9: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -1.79%): IF-stage JAL prediction that waits on imem_data adds opcode/immediate decode and a pc+imm adder to the fetch next-PC path while losing PC-only BTB coverage for jumps, so direct-JAL prediction must be earlier or cheaper than the BTB it replaces.\n10: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r4s0 (improvement, +2.75%): Collapsing parallel MUL-family products into one opcode-selected 33x33 signed multiply reduces ALU multiplier fanout and result mux pressure, so local datapath sharing can improve Tang Nano 20K fitness without changing CoreMark IPC.\n11: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (regression, -7.61%): A one-entry posted store buffer can lose to its MEM-stage dmem mux/control cost when ordering still stalls every younger memory op, so store decoupling needs enough independent non-memory slack to amortize the added critical-path logic.\n12: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -4.88%): Taken-only BTB allocation did not repay its extra update-hit compare/control in CoreMark, so direct-mapped predictor policies need measured aliasing relief before adding IF-stage update-path logic.\n13: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (regression, -7.68%): Removing regfile reset muxes regressed, so the 32x32 GPR reset fanout was not the active Tang Nano 20K limiter and resetless/initial-value inference can cost more than it saves for this small 2R1W file.\n14: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r5s1 (regression, -1.19%): Splitting execute and RVFI forwarding planes did not repay its extra source-mux/select fanout after load formatting was already optimized, so remove dmem cones only when the replacement control stays off the EX critical path.\n15: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -23.35%): Doubling the PC-only direct-mapped BTB/BHT from 16 to 32 entries widened the IF predictor arrays/index enough to swamp any CoreMark aliasing relief, so front-end capacity scaling must be timing-justified rather than assumed beneficial.\n16: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (improvement, +3.95%): Keeping the 16-entry BTB policy unchanged while comparing only pc[31:6] tags and storing word targets trims IF next-PC logic, so predictor representation micro-opts can beat behavior changes on this CoreMark front end.\n17: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (regression, -16.46%): A real IF/ID register can lose despite cutting imem-data-to-decode paths because the extra control-flow bubble and IF/ID hold/valid muxing outweigh modest iStall tolerance on CoreMark's BTB-assisted loops.\n18: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (regression, -3.52%): Narrowing 16-entry BTB tags down to pc[12:6] was too aggressive; any shorter IF comparator benefit was outweighed by added alias risk or synthesis cost, so keep enough PC entropy in predictor tags.\n19: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (improvement, +4.83%): Pruning truly dead control and inter-stage payload bits such as ctrl.is_lui and EX/MEM branch_taken/branch_target reduces flop fanout and routing pressure, so payload minimization remains a strong micro-opt when behavior is already encoded elsewhere.\n20: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (regression, -13.80%): Zero-bubble load-use forwarding made the MEM load-result path feed same-cycle EX operands and redirect control, so CoreMark bubble savings did not offset the longer dmem-to-EX critical path.\n21: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r7s2 (regression, -3.80%): Replacing the BTB's 2-bit counter with a 1-bit direction bit clears hot loop branches on single not-taken exits, so CoreMark still benefits from small predictor hysteresis even when the 16-entry PC-only BTB shape is timing-sensitive.\n22: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r8s0 (regression, -10.19%): Folding ctrl.mem_to_reg into ctrl.mem_read regressed because the load-enable control already drives memory/trap/stall logic, so keeping a separate low-fanout writeback-select bit can be faster than reusing a semantically equivalent hot control.\n23: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r8s1 (broken, n/a): Removing MEM/WB retirement also removes the held post-MEM producer needed to forward prior load/writeback data into ID/EX during dmem stalls, so a MEM-stage commit boundary still needs stable writeback state for backpressured dependents.\n24: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r8s2 (regression, -16.32%): Filtering conditional BTB updates to taken backedges undertrained CoreMark's forward branches and loop exits, so the 16-entry PC-only predictor needs broad conditional feedback more than reduced direct-mapped pollution.\n\n(End of file - total 24 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predecode may gate load-use stalls, but it must not mask RVFI rs1/rs2 fields because cosim expects raw instruction register fields and pre-write snapshots even when operands are unused.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (regression, +0.95%): A two-entry IF skid buffer added enough PC/buffer/valid-control muxing to outweigh its limited CoreMark benefit under random iStall, so fetch-ahead only helps if the core can exploit buffered instructions without extending the front-end critical path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (improvement, +0.96%): A tiny direct-mapped BTB helps CoreMark's repeated taken loops by avoiding warm branch redirects, but IF-side predictor lookup/update logic and aliasing keep the gain modest.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (improvement, +1.89%): Opcode-aware load-use gating recovers CoreMark bubbles from immediate/address-update code, but true load consumers still need raw RVFI source fields plus formatted MEM-stage load forwarding.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -40.43%): Pulling JAL/branch resolution into ID added regfile-compare, dependency-check, target-add, and IF redirect muxing onto the front-end path, so CoreMark control-flow savings did not offset the critical-path cost.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (broken, n/a): A fetch-stage RAS with IF-side JALR predecode and data-dependent stack indexing can make riscv-formal intractable, so predictor additions need solver-friendly state updates as well as correct architectural recovery.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (improvement, +4.91%): Replacing variable-shift load formatting with addr[1:0] lane muxes shortens the dmem-to-forwarding critical path for CoreMark's load-dependent code without changing MEM-stage semantics.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -17.42%): Moving DIV/REM into a sidecar can regress CoreMark when the divider is not the active critical path, because multi_stall gating and commit-result/operand muxes still sit on every EX instruction.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -1.79%): IF-stage JAL prediction that waits on imem_data adds opcode/immediate decode and a pc+imm adder to the fetch next-PC path while losing PC-only BTB coverage for jumps, so direct-JAL prediction must be earlier or cheaper than the BTB it replaces.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r4s0 (improvement, +2.75%): Collapsing parallel MUL-family products into one opcode-selected 33x33 signed multiply reduces ALU multiplier fanout and result mux pressure, so local datapath sharing can improve Tang Nano 20K fitness without changing CoreMark IPC.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (regression, -7.61%): A one-entry posted store buffer can lose to its MEM-stage dmem mux/control cost when ordering still stalls every younger memory op, so store decoupling needs enough independent non-memory slack to amortize the added critical-path logic.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -4.88%): Taken-only BTB allocation did not repay its extra update-hit compare/control in CoreMark, so direct-mapped predictor policies need measured aliasing relief before adding IF-stage update-path logic.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (regression, -7.68%): Removing regfile reset muxes regressed, so the 32x32 GPR reset fanout was not the active Tang Nano 20K limiter and resetless/initial-value inference can cost more than it saves for this small 2R1W file.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r5s1 (regression, -1.19%): Splitting execute and RVFI forwarding planes did not repay its extra source-mux/select fanout after load formatting was already optimized, so remove dmem cones only when the replacement control stays off the EX critical path.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -23.35%): Doubling the PC-only direct-mapped BTB/BHT from 16 to 32 entries widened the IF predictor arrays/index enough to swamp any CoreMark aliasing relief, so front-end capacity scaling must be timing-justified rather than assumed beneficial.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (improvement, +3.95%): Keeping the 16-entry BTB policy unchanged while comparing only pc[31:6] tags and storing word targets trims IF next-PC logic, so predictor representation micro-opts can beat behavior changes on this CoreMark front end.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (regression, -16.46%): A real IF/ID register can lose despite cutting imem-data-to-decode paths because the extra control-flow bubble and IF/ID hold/valid muxing outweigh modest iStall tolerance on CoreMark's BTB-assisted loops.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (regression, -3.52%): Narrowing 16-entry BTB tags down to pc[12:6] was too aggressive; any shorter IF comparator benefit was outweighed by added alias risk or synthesis cost, so keep enough PC entropy in predictor tags.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (improvement, +4.83%): Pruning truly dead control and inter-stage payload bits such as ctrl.is_lui and EX/MEM branch_taken/branch_target reduces flop fanout and routing pressure, so payload minimization remains a strong micro-opt when behavior is already encoded elsewhere.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (regression, -13.80%): Zero-bubble load-use forwarding made the MEM load-result path feed same-cycle EX operands and redirect control, so CoreMark bubble savings did not offset the longer dmem-to-EX critical path.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778659908555,"end":1778659908563}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_031bf222e0c1707a016a0432446f148199b410cb9bd3ac8a20"}},"id":"prt_e20645bc2001wIrn4n5CPH0Ut5","sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","messageID":"msg_e20640a37001UjsWCAyZdiaSPP"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778659908572,"sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_8t9Ly6wt9kYGVuRu4m3jw69U","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"\"category\"\\s*:\\s*\"structural\"|category:\\s*structural|structural","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments","include":"*.jsonl"},"output":"Found 8 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\\ninserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\\ninstruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\\ndmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\\nis a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\\nthe single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core directly couples the PC/IF output to decode and\\ninserts a bubble whenever io_imemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode,\\ninstruction fetch sees about 22% random stalls, and downstream load-use or\\ndmem stalls also prevent useful fetch-ahead. A small instruction skid buffer\\nis a structural change that can hide some of that latency without changing\\nthe single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure IF into a decoupled fetch producer plus a one- or two-entry\\nvalid/pc/instruction buffer feeding ID. When ID is stalled by load-use or\\ndmem backpressure and imem is ready, IF should continue advancing and enqueue\\nsequential instructions; when imemReady drops, ID can consume a buffered\\ninstruction instead of immediately receiving a bubble. Redirects must flush\\nthe buffer and restart at the redirect target. This should improve CoreMark\\niterations/cycle under the apples-to-apples random iStall model while adding\\nonly a few registers and muxes, with limited Fmax risk.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the direct combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid/pc/instruction skid buffer, preserving redirect priority and flushing buffered wrong-path entries.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Separate fetch-side stalls from decode-side stalls so imem backpressure only st...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve simple control flow in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline resolves every branch and jump in EX, so taken control\\nflow still carries a two-stage wrong-path penalty unless the BTB predicts it\\ncorrectly. The prior structural fetch skid buffer lost because it added IF\\ncontrol and muxing without shortening a common dependency path. CoreMark has\\nmany loop branches and unconditional jumps, so structurally moving simple\\ntarget/condition resolution one stage earlier can improve iterations/cycle\\nwithout widening retirement or adding front-end buffering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline resolves every branch and jump in EX, so taken control\\nflow still carries a two-stage wrong-path penalty unless the BTB predicts it\\ncorrectly. The prior structural fetch skid buffer lost because it added IF\\ncontrol and muxing without shortening a common dependency path. CoreMark has\\nmany loop branches and unconditional jumps, so structurally moving simple\\ntarget/condition resolution one stage earlier can improve iterations/cycle\\nwithout widening retirement or adding front-end buffering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an early-control path in ID for JAL and branch instructions whose operands\\nare already available from the regfile or WB write-first bypass, and redirect\\nIF before the instruction reaches EX. ID/EX should carry an early-resolved\\nnext PC plus a flag so EX can skip reissuing the same redirect while still\\npreserving the existing EX resolution for forwarded operands, load-use cases,\\nJALR, misalignment traps, and predictor updates. This reduces taken JAL and\\nmany non-dependent loop branch penalties by one cycle while keeping the\\nsingle-retire RVFI boundary and trap discipline unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ID/EX metadata for an early-resolved next PC and whether E...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Move div/rem off EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU keeps RV32M division and remainder as single-cycle\\ncombinational operations in the EX stage. CoreMark's timed path is dominated\\nby loads, branches, integer ALU work, and multiplication, while DIV/REM are\\nrare or absent. Keeping a full divider on every EX-cycle timing path likely\\ncosts Fmax and LUTs without improving CoreMark iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU keeps RV32M division and remainder as single-cycle\\ncombinational operations in the EX stage. CoreMark's timed path is dominated\\nby loads, branches, integer ALU work, and multiplication, while DIV/REM are\\nrare or absent. Keeping a full divider on every EX-cycle timing path likely\\ncosts Fmax and LUTs without improving CoreMark iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the M-extension structure so common ALU operations and MUL/MULH stay on\\nthe existing one-cycle EX path, but DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU are handled by a small\\nmulti-cycle divider sidecar that stalls the pipeline only when one of those\\nopcodes reaches EX. This should remove the long combinational divide/remainder\\nnetwork from the EX/MEM register timing path and recover FPGA Fmax, while\\npreserving CoreMark IPC because the benchmark should not depend on frequent\\ndivisions. The sidecar must keep RV32M corner-case results exact, keep ALTOPS\\nbehavior for fast formal runs, and retire the original instruction only after\\nthe computed result is available.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact control metadata, if needed, to identify DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as multi-cycle EX operations without changing the NRET=1 RVFI bundle shape.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM from the one-cycle combinational ALU path while keeping normal ALU, MUL-family, and RISCV_FORM...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Post ordinary RAM stores\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes the entire core whenever a store sits in MEM\\nand io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode dmem has random\\nbackpressure, and CoreMark contains many stores whose results are not\\nimmediately consumed by the next integer instructions. Prior structural\\nattempts regressed by lengthening the fetch/control critical path; this\\ntargets a different bottleneck by decoupling store acceptance from the\\nrest of the in-order pipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes the entire core whenever a store sits in MEM\\nand io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark cosim mode dmem has random\\nbackpressure, and CoreMark contains many stores whose results are not\\nimmediately consumed by the next integer instructions. Prior structural\\nattempts regressed by lengthening the fetch/control critical path; this\\ntargets a different bottleneck by decoupling store acceptance from the\\nrest of the in-order pipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry posted store buffer for aligned, non-MMIO RAM stores. When a\\nstore reaches MEM while dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated\\nwrite data, byte mask, and RVFI store fields, allow the store to retire once\\nit is safely enqueued, and continue executing independent non-memory\\ninstructions while the buffer drains to dmem in the background. Preserve\\narchitectural ordering by stalling any later load or store until the buffer\\nis empty, and never post UART or CoreMark timing-marker MMIO stores so the\\nstart/stop bracket remains tied to real bus writes. This should improve\\nCoreMark iterations/cycle under random dStall without adding predictor or\\nbranch-resolution logic to the critical IF path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one-entry posted store buffer for aligned nor...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Split execute and RVFI forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current forwarding network uses the MEM-stage formatted writeback value for\\nboth execute operands and RVFI source snapshots. That keeps the dmem read-data\\nformatting path connected to the EX operand muxes even though true load-use\\nconsumers are already stalled until the load reaches MEM/WB. Prior wins show\\nthat the dmem-to-forwarding path matters, while prior broken source-use work\\nshows RVFI raw source snapshots must still be preserved.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current forwarding network uses the MEM-stage formatted writeback value for\\nboth execute operands and RVFI source snapshots. That keeps the dmem read-data\\nformatting path connected to the EX operand muxes even though true load-use\\nconsumers are already stalled until the load reaches MEM/WB. Prior wins show\\nthat the dmem-to-forwarding path matters, while prior broken source-use work\\nshows RVFI raw source snapshots must still be preserved.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure forwarding into two planes: an execute plane that forwards only\\nALU/JAL results from EX/MEM and WB data from MEM/WB, and an RVFI snapshot\\nplane that can still forward the formatted MEM-stage load value for raw rs1\\nand rs2 reporting. EX should use the execute plane for ALU operands, branch\\ncompares, JALR targets, and store write data; the separately computed RVFI\\noperands should be carried in ex_mem_t.rs1_val/rs2_val exactly as today. This\\nremoves the load-format/dmem_rdata cone from common execute timing without\\nchanging retirement width, load-use interlocks, memory ordering, or RVFI\\nsource-field semantics.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Produce separate execute-forwarding and RVFI-source-forwarding selects, suppressing EX/MEM load selection only on the execute plane.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Register IF/ID boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core currently has a PC register in IF, but the IF/ID payload is\\ncombinational: imem data, raw instruction fields, decoder outputs, immediate\\ngeneration, and regfile read addresses all feed the ID/EX register in one\\ncycle. Prior structural attempts that added predictors, buffers, or early\\ncontrol logic regressed because they lengthened IF-side muxing or broad\\npipeline control. A narrower structural retiming can attack the same frontend\\ntiming pressure without adding a larger predictor or side buffer.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core currently has a PC register in IF, but the IF/ID payload is\\ncombinational: imem data, raw instruction fields, decoder outputs, immediate\\ngeneration, and regfile read addresses all feed the ID/EX register in one\\ncycle. Prior structural attempts that added predictors, buffers, or early\\ncontrol logic regressed because they lengthened IF-side muxing or broad\\npipeline control. A narrower structural retiming can attack the same frontend\\ntiming pressure without adding a larger predictor or side buffer.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert IF/ID into a true registered pipeline boundary that captures pc,\\npredicted pc, instruction, and valid when imem is ready, holds across ID or\\ndmem stalls, and flushes on redirects. This cuts the imem-data-to-decode and\\nimem-data-to-regfile-address path out of the ID/EX setup cone, and the single\\nregistered entry can also let ID consume one already-fetched instruction when\\nthe next imem access stalls. The cost is one extra frontend stage and a larger\\nredirect bubble on unpredicted control flow, but CoreMark's hot loop branches\\nare already helped by the existing BTB, so the expected net gain is higher\\nFmax plus modest iStall tolerance with much less control complexity than the\\nearlier skid-buffer attempt.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"me...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Use zero-bubble load forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline still injects a one-cycle bubble for every true load-use\\ndependency even though MEM-stage forwarding already formats load data and can\\nfeed the EX operand muxes. CoreMark has many pointer-chasing and state-update\\nsequences where removing those bubbles should improve iterations per cycle.\\nPrior structural attempts lost by adding front-end or store-buffer control;\\nthis keeps the pipeline shape intact and changes only the interlock policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline still injects a one-cycle bubble for every true load-use\\ndependency even though MEM-stage forwarding already formats load data and can\\nfeed the EX operand muxes. CoreMark has many pointer-chasing and state-update\\nsequences where removing those bubbles should improve iterations per cycle.\\nPrior structural attempts lost by adding front-end or store-buffer control;\\nthis keeps the pipeline shape intact and changes only the interlock policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure the load-use path so a consumer immediately behind a load is\\nallowed to enter EX while the load is in MEM, using the existing EX/MEM\\nforwarding select to supply formatted load data directly from mem_stage.\\nIf dmem backpressure occurs, the existing dmem stall should hold both the\\nload in MEM and the dependent consumer in ID/EX until data is available, so\\ncorrectness remains in-order without adding a new buffer. This trades a\\nlonger dmem-to-EX bypass path for fewer CoreMark dependency bubbles; the\\nprevious lane-mux load formatter win makes that timing path cheaper than it\\nwas before.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unconditional load-use bubble and rely on dmem stalls plus MEM-stage load forwarding for true dependent consumers.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\"...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Retire directly from MEM\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current bench core still carries a full MEM/WB register and a separate\\ncombinational WB stage even though MEM already computes the final writeback\\nvalue, formatted load data, memory masks, and RVFI memory fields. Recent wins\\ncame from pruning dead pipeline payload and shortening local datapath cones,\\nwhile prior structural regressions came from adding front-end buffers,\\nearlier branch logic, store buffers, or same-cycle dmem-to-EX pressure. A\\nMEM-stage retirement boundary attacks pipeline structure and routing pressure\\nwithout adding predictor state or changing the NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current bench core still carries a full MEM/WB register and a separate\\ncombinational WB stage even though MEM already computes the final writeback\\nvalue, formatted load data, memory masks, and RVFI memory fields. Recent wins\\ncame from pruning dead pipeline payload and shortening local datapath cones,\\nwhile prior structural regressions came from adding front-end buffers,\\nearlier branch logic, store buffers, or same-cycle dmem-to-EX pressure. A\\nMEM-stage retirement boundary attacks pipeline structure and routing pressure\\nwithout adding predictor state or changing the NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Collapse writeback/retirement into the MEM stage: compute the final rd write\\ndata from the current EX/MEM payload, write the regfile from that MEM-stage\\ncommit value, and drive RVFI channel 0 from the same commit record when the\\nmemory operation is actually accepted. Keep the existing one-cycle load-use\\ninterlock, but remove the broad MEM/WB payload and replace MEM/WB forwarding\\nwith MEM-stage forwarding plus the regfile's same-cycle write-first bypass\\nfor instructions two cycles behind a producer. This should reduce flop count,\\nforwarding mux fan-in, and routing fanout on every instruction while keeping\\nCoreMark's steady...","metadata":{"matches":8,"truncated":false},"title":"\"category\"\\s*:\\s*\"structural\"|category:\\s*structural|structural","time":{"start":1778659908559,"end":1778659908571}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_031bf222e0c1707a016a0432446f2481999d424940c997bb73"}},"id":"prt_e20645bcc0012Aic33Ivk0D81f","sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","messageID":"msg_e20640a37001UjsWCAyZdiaSPP"}}
