{"type":"text","timestamp":1778659947105,"sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","part":{"id":"prt_e2064ea4f001V2LsfH76m6fkct","messageID":"msg_e20645c3f0020G0HYf6KKSKGyP","sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","type":"text","text":"Structural history is mostly negative: front-end buffering/retiming, early ID control, store buffering, zero-bubble load-use, and MEM retirement collapse all regressed or broke. The strongest positive pattern is structural payload/routing reduction, so I’m going to propose a narrowly-scoped stage split/prune that removes hot control fanout rather than adding new queueing or predictor behavior.","time":{"start":1778659945039,"end":1778659947102},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0089b4c893efffcf016a043268ecf4819bab51bbbe352edb4e","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778659997426,"sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","part":{"id":"prt_e2065b1df001PYmr7s1hu7jDiw","messageID":"msg_e20645c3f0020G0HYf6KKSKGyP","sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a structural hypothesis to pipeline the BTB update path by one cycle. This keeps redirect timing unchanged but moves counter/tag write logic off the same-cycle EX-to-IF state-update path.","time":{"start":1778659996127,"end":1778659997423},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0089b4c893efffcf016a04329c00f4819bbb5dde50ce889e12","phase":"commentary"}}}}
