{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778660041025,"sessionID":"ses_1df9bf602ffejnJjrkPDCM8cDw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_dzbOgMQ6i0F4IqaWgBg9aKNz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r9s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r9s1\n+title: \"Pipeline BTB update path\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added front-end buffering, early control resolution, store posting, or zero-bubble load-use forwarding either lengthened hot paths or disturbed required stall/forwarding behavior. The existing 16-entry BTB is still useful, but its same-cycle update path takes EX-stage branch results, computes update index/tag/target, compares the old tag, and drives counter/entry write data in the IF module. That path can cost Fmax without improving the current cycle's redirect decision.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Insert a one-cycle registered BTB update queue inside if_stage. EX still produces redirect and redirect_target in the same cycle, so architectural recovery and RVFI pc_wdata behavior are unchanged, but bpu_update_valid/pc/taken/target are first captured into a small update register and the BTB tag/target/counter arrays are written from that register on the following cycle. This removes the branch-compare/target cone from the direct BTB array write-data path while preserving the existing 16-entry direct-mapped predictor policy, two-bit hysteresis, tag width, and fetch next-PC lookup. CoreMark loop bodies should rarely refetch the same branch before a one-cycle-delayed update becomes visible, so the expected IPC loss is minimal while Fmax may improve.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry registered BTB update path and drive BTB tag/target/counter writes from the delayed update instead of same-cycle EX update signals.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r9s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r9s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r9s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r9s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,13 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r9s1\n+title: \"Pipeline BTB update path\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added front-end buffering, early control resolution, store posting, or zero-bubble load-use forwarding either lengthened hot paths or disturbed required stall/forwarding behavior. The existing 16-entry BTB is still useful, but its same-cycle update path takes EX-stage branch results, computes update index/tag/target, compares the old tag, and drives counter/entry write data in the IF module. That path can cost Fmax without improving the current cycle's redirect decision.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Insert a one-cycle registered BTB update queue inside if_stage. EX still produces redirect and redirect_target in the same cycle, so architectural recovery and RVFI pc_wdata behavior are unchanged, but bpu_update_valid/pc/taken/target are first captured into a small update register and the BTB tag/target/counter arrays are written from that register on the following cycle. This removes the branch-compare/target cone from the direct BTB array write-data path while preserving the existing 16-entry direct-mapped predictor policy, two-bit hysteresis, tag width, and fetch next-PC lookup. CoreMark loop bodies should rarely refetch the same branch before a one-cycle-delayed update bec