{"type":"text","timestamp":1778662194063,"sessionID":"ses_1df7a48a5ffe1zgYNfYJU84dlm","part":{"id":"prt_e20873b27002lq3PcY10687dLB","messageID":"msg_e20861d8c001YnNrlGOlto6C1q","sessionID":"ses_1df7a48a5ffe1zgYNfYJU84dlm","type":"text","text":"The history points away from larger tables, IF instruction predecode, RAS, delayed updates, and narrower tags. The remaining low-risk predictor slot is a policy-only tweak that keeps the existing PC-only lookup and table shape intact.","time":{"start":1778662193959,"end":1778662194063},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0544636a0bf6777f016a043b31da9c819b8a7a08eb3b1f29d7","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778662232831,"sessionID":"ses_1df7a48a5ffe1zgYNfYJU84dlm","part":{"id":"prt_e2087cefa001tljLEEWEqgBOv1","messageID":"msg_e20861d8c001YnNrlGOlto6C1q","sessionID":"ses_1df7a48a5ffe1zgYNfYJU84dlm","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a single-file predictor hypothesis that changes only BTB counter initialization on allocation, avoiding any new IF lookup logic or extra predictor state.","time":{"start":1778662231802,"end":1778662232829},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0544636a0bf6777f016a043b57afc4819bb13ffe626b894c39","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778662251417,"sessionID":"ses_1df7a48a5ffe1zgYNfYJU84dlm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_tghOsCI0vu3sTrve58NTolkt","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r10s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r10s2\n+title: \"Strong-bias BTB allocations\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The existing 16-entry PC-only BTB with compact tags and two-bit counters is the only predictor shape that has improved this core. Recent predictor regressions came from changing table size, adding IF-side instruction predecode, weakening hysteresis, filtering feedback, or delaying updates. A safer remaining predictor angle is to preserve the lookup path and state shape while changing only the initial counter bias on newly allocated taken entries.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Initialize a newly allocated taken BTB entry to strongly taken instead of weakly taken, while keeping not-taken allocations, matching-entry training, tags, targets, entry count, and EX-stage updates unchanged. This gives short CoreMark loops and call/branch sites one extra bit of hysteresis immediately after the first taken observation, so a single loop-exit not-taken update is less likely to poison the next loop entry. Because the fetch lookup still reads the same valid/tag/target/counter arrays and uses the same counter MSB, the change should have almost no Fmax risk and may recover a small amount of branch IPC.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 1\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change BTB allocation for newly observed taken control-flow entries from weak-taken to strong-taken, leaving lookup logic, table size, tags, targets, and normal saturating counter training unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r10s2.yaml","metadata":{"d