{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778664471655,"sessionID":"ses_1df566422ffejxgluJbweNa1X0","part":{"id":"prt_e20a9fc64001vlvuz93FNkJ1VU","messageID":"msg_e20a9f7e5001eascQ17PY7l71F","sessionID":"ses_1df566422ffejxgluJbweNa1X0","snapshot":"d22f4742d43dd6bffbf8cbfadb078ac328c3c421","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778664503375,"sessionID":"ses_1df566422ffejxgluJbweNa1X0","part":{"id":"prt_e20aa6ee3001C9Z6XfIiKGhOEh","messageID":"msg_e20a9f7e5001eascQ17PY7l71F","sessionID":"ses_1df566422ffejxgluJbweNa1X0","type":"text","text":"The relevant predictor history shows the current 16-entry PC-only BTB is useful, while larger tables, IF instruction predecode, RAS, weaker hysteresis, filtered updates, delayed updates, and counter rebiasing all regressed. I’m going to keep the proven lookup shape and target the remaining low-risk predictor issue: destructive direct-map aliasing with a very small victim entry instead of widening the main table.","time":{"start":1778664500963,"end":1778664503374},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_06c927d3eb1c0128016a044434db94819a954a6fa7b84b392a","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778664555900,"sessionID":"ses_1df566422ffejxgluJbweNa1X0","part":{"id":"prt_e20ab3e520012ARRutvGb25DWi","messageID":"msg_e20a9f7e5001eascQ17PY7l71F","sessionID":"ses_1df566422ffejxgluJbweNa1X0","type":"text","text":"I’ll write the hypothesis file now. It will only target `rtl/if_stage.sv`, because the existing EX-to-IF predictor update interface already carries enough information for a victim-entry BTB sidecar.","time":{"start":1778664554066,"end":1778664555900},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_06c927d3eb1c0128016a044469f53c819a9df6bf6ae57198c3","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778664578344,"sessionID":"ses_1df566422ffejxgluJbweNa1X0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_P6OOzy3EM4I2CJdHelZR9gvZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r11s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r11s2\n+title: \"Add one-entry BTB victim\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current compact 16-entry PC-only BTB is the only predictor shape that has\n+  reliably improved this core, but the lessons show direct-mapped aliasing is\n+  still the likely remaining predictor limiter. Prior attempts to reduce that\n+  aliasing by widening the table, narrowing tags, filtering updates, changing\n+  hysteresis, adding IF instruction predecode, or adding RAS state all regressed.\n+  A tiny victim entry attacks only conflict misses while preserving the proven\n+  main BTB size, tag width, 2-bit counters, and EX-stage update discipline.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single fully tagged victim BTB entry beside the existing 16-entry direct\n+  mapped BTB. On a main-table replacement, copy the evicted valid entry into the\n+  victim slot with its PC word tag, target word, and 2-bit counter. During fetch,\n+  keep the current main BTB lookup as priority, and on a main miss allow a victim\n+  hit with a taken counter to supply the predicted target. Updates that match the\n+  victim entry train its counter and target in place; other updates continue to\n+  allocate and train the main table as today. This should recover hot two-branch\n+  index conflicts in CoreMark without the broad IF path and routing cost of a\n+  32-entry table or the formal/timing risk of instruction-dependent prediction.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry fully tagged victim BTB sidecar that captures evicted main-table entries, participates only after main BTB misses, and trains through the existing EX-stage predictor update signals.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r11s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r11s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r11s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r11s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r11s2\n+title: \"Add one-entry BTB victim\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current compact 16-entry PC-only BTB is the only predictor shape that has\n+  reliably improved this core, but the lessons show direct-mapped aliasing is\n+  still the likely remaining predictor limiter. Prior attempts to reduce that\n+  aliasing by widening the table, narrowing tags, filtering updates, changing\n+  hysteresis, adding IF instruction predecode, or adding RAS state all regressed.\n+  A tiny victim entry attacks only conflict misses while preserving the proven\n+  main BTB size, tag width, 2-bit counters, and EX-stage update discipline.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single fully tagged victim BTB entry beside the existing 16-entry direct\n+  mapped BTB. On a main-table replacement, copy the evicted valid entry into the\n+  victim slot with its PC word tag, target word, and 2-bit counter. During fetch,\n+  keep the current main BTB lookup as priority, and on a main miss allow a victim\n+  hit with a taken counter to supply the predicted target. Updates that match the\n+  victim entry train its counter and target in place; other updates continue to\n+  allocate and train the main table as today. 