{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778673160788,"sessionID":"ses_1ded2956cffehN1o8E0WcIxpai","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_s7ew9axmopZj6aQber85F9Wh","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r14s2\n+title: \"Shrink BTB to eight entries\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The existing compact PC-only BTB remains the only predictor shape with a durable\n+  win, but recent predictor attempts show that extra capacity, policy state,\n+  delayed updates, victim entries, RAS state, IF instruction decode, and compare\n+  gating all cost more than CoreMark repays. The remaining safe direction is to\n+  reduce the predictor's IF-side lookup and update footprint while preserving the\n+  same simple direct-mapped behavior.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Reduce the current 16-entry direct-mapped BTB/BHT to 8 entries by changing only\n+  the entry count and index width in if_stage. Keep compact non-index tags,\n+  word-aligned targets, 2-bit counters, EX-stage updates, redirect priority, and\n+  predicted-next-PC validation unchanged. If CoreMark's timed hot loop working set\n+  fits in the smaller table, the shorter indexed muxes, fewer predictor flops, and\n+  narrower reset/update routing should improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax with little IPC\n+  loss, avoiding the failed directions that added front-end logic or extra state.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change the BTB entry count and index width from 16/4 to 8/3 while preserving compact tags, word targets, 2-bit counter policy, EX updates, and redirect recovery.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5