{"type":"text","timestamp":1778652308597,"sessionID":"ses_1e00ff872ffeXam1Al3TgYeSur","part":{"id":"prt_e1ff0634d001gIEZj0sV7OeRs3","messageID":"msg_e1ff02736001pQCv83cnVUerCc","sessionID":"ses_1e00ff872ffeXam1Al3TgYeSur","type":"text","text":"The predictor history points away from more BTB capacity, IF opcode predecode, or RAS speculation. The most promising predictor-only angle is to keep the 16-entry PC-only lookup policy but shrink the stored tag from full 32-bit PC to the low program-window bits, cutting IF comparator/register cost without increasing CoreMark aliasing inside the 6 KB benchmark image.","time":{"start":1778652308301,"end":1778652308594},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_05cedaabcf600b69016a04149435c0819bb550b4037772508c","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778652314599,"sessionID":"ses_1e00ff872ffeXam1Al3TgYeSur","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_B8bSI4MWlrvLV9HhCY2gJ1G3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\n+title: \"Narrow BTB tags\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current successful predictor is a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB/BHT, but\n+  every IF cycle still performs a full 32-bit PC tag comparison before choosing\n+  the predicted target. Prior predictor attempts show that larger tables,\n+  fetched-instruction predecode, taken-only allocation policy, and RAS state add\n+  more front-end/control cost than CoreMark repays. CoreMark's timed image is a\n+  small 6 KB working set in low memory, so a full 32-bit tag is unnecessary for\n+  distinguishing useful in-image control-flow PCs.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the BTB's stored full-PC tag with a compact low-address tag derived\n+  from bits above the 16-entry index, for example pc[12:6]. Keep the same entry\n+  count, target storage, 2-bit counters, EX-stage update policy, redirect\n+  recovery, and predicted-next-PC metadata. This preserves the predictor behavior\n+  for unique branch PCs within the CoreMark code window while shortening the IF\n+  hit comparator and reducing predictor flip-flops/LUT fanout, so Fmax should\n+  improve without repeating the IPC regressions from capacity or policy changes.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Store and compare a narrow BTB tag such as pc[12:6] instead of the full fetch PC, leaving table size, counters, targets, and update semantics unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\n+title: \"Narrow BTB tags\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current successful predictor is a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB/BHT, but\n+  every IF cycle still performs a full 32-bit PC tag comparison before choosing\n+  the predicted target. Prior predictor attempts show that larger tables,\n+  fetched-instruction predecode, taken-only allocation policy, and RAS state add\n+  more front-end/control cost than CoreMark repays. CoreMark's timed image is a\n+  small 6 KB working set in low memory, so a full 32-bit tag is unnecessary for\n+  distinguishing useful in-image control-flow PCs.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the BTB's stored full-PC tag with a compact low-address tag derived\n+  from bits above the 16-entry index, for example pc[12:6]. Keep the same entry\n+  count, target storage, 2-bit counters, EX-stage update policy, redirect\n+  recovery, and predicted-next-PC metadata. This preserves the predictor behavior\n+  for unique branch PCs within the CoreMark code window while shortening the IF\n+  hit comparator and reducing predictor flip-flops/LUT fanout, so Fmax should\n+  improve without repeating the IPC regressions from capacity or policy changes.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Store and compare a narrow BTB tag such as pc[12:6] instead of the full fetch PC, leaving table size, counters, targets, and update semantics unchanged.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\n+title: \"Narrow BTB tags\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current successful predictor is a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB/BHT, but\n+  every IF cycle still performs a full 32-bit PC tag comparison before choosing\n+  the predicted target. Prior predictor attempts show that larger tables,\n+  fetched-instruction predecode, taken-only allocation policy, and RAS state add\n+  more front-end/control cost than CoreMark repays. CoreMark's timed image is a\n+  small 6 KB working set in low memory, so a full 32-bit tag is unnecessary for\n+  distinguishing useful in-image control-flow PCs.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the BTB's stored full-PC tag with a compact low-address tag derived\n+  from bits above the 16-entry index, for example pc[12:6]. Keep the same entry\n+  count, target storage, 2-bit counters, EX-stage update policy, redirect\n+  recovery, and predicted-next-PC metadata. This preserves the predictor behavior\n+  for unique branch PCs within the CoreMark code window while shortening the IF\n+  hit comparator and reducing predictor flip-flops/LUT fanout, so Fmax should\n+  improve without repeating the IPC regressions from capacity or policy changes.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Store and compare a narrow BTB tag such as pc[12:6] instead of the full fetch PC, leaving table size, counters, targets, and update semantics unchanged.\"\n","additions":25,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r6s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778652314592,"end":1778652314598}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05cedaabcf600b69016a0414962b7c819baaf5463d58545270"}},"id":"prt_e1ff06afd001wBH7Uwgx8KgSll","sessionID":"ses_1e00ff872ffeXam1Al3TgYeSur","messageID":"msg_e1ff02736001pQCv83cnVUerCc"}}
