{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778654521106,"sessionID":"ses_1dfef2d61ffeP65ImCxXYnNqeR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_3tlPjvl9Yx6p8wUBOfg7Cwas","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\n+title: \"Simplify BTB direction state\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The useful predictor changes so far point toward preserving the small PC-only\n+  BTB and trimming its lookup representation rather than adding fetch predecode,\n+  return-stack state, or more entries. The current IF path still reads a 2-bit\n+  counter per entry and gates the hit target through the counter MSB, while the\n+  update path contains saturating increment/decrement logic for every resolved\n+  control-flow instruction. CoreMark's hot backward branches are mostly taken and\n+  already recover from loop exits by keeping the target resident, so a simpler\n+  direction representation may trade a small amount of hysteresis for better Fmax.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the BTB's 2-bit saturating counters with a one-bit direction bit while\n+  keeping the existing 16-entry direct-mapped tag and word-target arrays. Predict\n+  a BTB hit only when the resident direction bit is set, allocate or set the bit\n+  on taken updates, and clear it on matching not-taken updates without allocating\n+  not-taken misses. This preserves the PC-only IF lookup and avoids the failed\n+  larger-table, RAS, and IF-instruction-predecode directions, while removing the\n+  counter add/sub/compare logic and one prediction-state bit per entry from the\n+  front-end predictor cone.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 1\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the 2-bit BTB/BHT counters with one-bit direction state, update it on matching outcomes, allocate only taken misses, and use hit-and-direction for the predicted next PC.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\n+title: \"Simplify BTB direction state\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The useful predictor changes so far point toward preserving the small PC-only\n+  BTB and trimming its lookup representation rather than adding fetch predecode,\n+  return-stack state, or more entries. The current IF path still reads a 2-bit\n+  counter per entry and gates the hit target through the counter MSB, while the\n+  update path contains saturating increment/decrement logic for every resolved\n+  control-flow instruction. CoreMark's hot backward branches are mostly taken and\n+  already recover from loop exits by keeping the target resident, so a simpler\n+  direction representation may trade a small amount of hysteresis for better Fmax.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the BTB's 2-bit saturating counters with a one-bit direction bit while\n+  keeping the existing 16-entry direct-mapped tag and word-target arrays. Predict\n+  a BTB hit only when the resident direction bit is set, allocate or set the bit\n+  on taken updates, and clear it on matching not-taken updates without allocating\n+  not-taken misses. This preserves the PC-only IF lookup and avoids the failed\n+  larger-table, RAS